05683nam a22007575i 9780774862790DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748627907 a10.59962/97807748627902doi  a(DE-B1597)661966  a(OCoLC)1132272296  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD810.W7bM343 2020 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a940.53082/097122300aMaking the Best of It :bWomen and Girls of Canada and Newfoundland during the Second World War /ced. by Sarah Glassford, Amy Shaw. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (310 p.) :b20 b&w photo, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Canadian Military History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tWomen, Children, and the War -- tThe Small Spaces of Childhood -- tFostering Friendships -- tCasualties of War -- tCivic Identities in Conflict -- tWomen and the War at Home -- t“A Token Jew Everywhere” -- tShopping to Win the War -- tMrs. Consumer Goes to War -- tWomen and Overseas Humanitarian Work -- tResponding to “War’s Havoc” -- t“It Keeps Our Spirits Up” -- tWomen in Wartime Nursing, Paid War Work, and the Armed Forces -- t“War Comes to Labrador” -- tThey Died so That Men May Fight -- t“Keep Your Mind on Your Job” -- tConclusion -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tStudies In Canadian Military History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany women who lived through the Second World War believed it heralded new status and opportunities, but scholars have argued that very little changed. How can these interpretations be reconciled? Making the Best of It examines the ways in which gender and other identities intersected to shape the experiences of female Canadians and Newfoundlanders during the war. The contributors to this thoughtful collection consider mainstream and minority populations, girls and women, and different parts of Canada and Newfoundland. They reassess topics such as women in the military and in munitions factories, and tackle entirely new subjects such as wartime girlhood in Quebec. Collectively, these essays broaden the scope of what we know about the changes the war wrought in the lives of Canadian women and girls, and address wider debates about memory, historiography, and feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomenzNewfoundland and LabradorxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWomenzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWomenzNewfoundland and Labrador. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aBroad, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoombs, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpp, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlassford, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlassford, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalstead, Claire L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogenbirk, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenzkowski, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasolli, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShaw, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l